<TEXT>
prime minister margaret thatchers government has 
decided to defy the unelected house of lords and reintroduce a bill 
to allow the prosecution of elderly suspected nazi war criminals 
living in britain 
sir geoffrey howe conservative leader of the house of commons 
announced thursday night the government intends during the next 
session of parliament to resubmit the war crimes bill which was 
easily defeated by the lords on june 5 
the lords powers are limited to delaying legislation for one 
year 
the elected house of commons had approved a governmentappointed 
commissions recommendation to prosecute war criminals passing the 
bill last december by a 27060 vote 
but a succession of peers including lawyers who prosecuted the 
top nazis at postwar trials in nuremberg or fought in world war ii 
as young officers opposed the bill saying fair trials were 
impossible and dragging aging emigres before courts would only stir 
old hatreds 
the bill was defeated in the lords by a vote of 20774 
howe told the house of commons the government will be 
seeking whether by suggested amendments or otherwise to secure 
that the bill next session may receive the support of both houses 
if the lords again vote against the bill however the 
government is likely to use its powers under the parliament act 
not invoked for more than 40 years to force it through 
the simon wiesenthal society which seeks prosecution of 
suspected nazi war criminals applauded the governments decision 
to reintroduce the bill 
this decision sends a strong signal that after 40 years of 
apathy and delay the people of great britain will finally stand 
with the victims of the holocaust by bringing those who 
participated in nazi genocide before the bar of justice rabbi 
abraham cooper associate dean of the los angelesbased wiesenthal 
center said in a statement issued friday 
britain is the only world war ii ally without laws to prosecute 
suspected war criminals canada and australia recently changed laws 
to allow trials and the united states deports suspects for trial to 
israel or other countries 
the government commission headed by a former director of public 
prosecutions said there is sufficient evidence to prosecute three 
suspects living in britain and 124 more should be investigated the 
suspects allegedly helped round up and murder thousands of jews in 
nazioccupied soviet republics 
</TEXT>
