<TEXT>
shirli and mazal are crawling on the sleeping 
bags and blankets sprawled on the tent floor the girls mother 
michal ovadiya stares absently at the khaki wall of the tent her 
home 
tent camps are the latest form of protest by israelis pushed out 
of their rented homes by inflated housing prices caused by the 
wave of soviet jewish immigrants 
there are three militarytype tents and about a dozen families 
at this encampment in a garden across from israels parliament a 
halfdozen such camps have sprung up across the country to house 
homeless israelis and to call attention to their plight 
rents have doubled and even tripled throughout israel with the 
arrival of more than 56000 soviet jews since the start of 1989 a 
total of 150000 are expected to arrive this year 
the immigrants who get a government housing subsidy of about 
237 a month soon caused a shortage in modestpriced units 
landlords raised the rents of their cheapest apartments to match 
the subsidy causing an overall increase in housing prices 
many israelis say they cannot compete with the soviets who also 
get their subsidy a full year in advance and are thus forced to 
leave their homes 
the sun is blazing and it is hard to breathe inside the tent 
which is shared by ms ovadiya her daughters and four other 
people it is filled to capacity with sleeping bags one corner is 
taken by a wooden crib 
tent life is dull the residents make coffee on a portable stove 
hooked to a tank of cooking gas there is not much food slices of 
bread chocolate butter a watermelon there is no running water 
a newcomer dressed in a tshirt and shorts asks if there is a 
place available then announces that he will join the tent dwellers 
next week with his wife and two children 
i dont know what to do i dont have anywhere to go said 
ms ovadiya a darkskinned 30yearold divorcee i feel like 
she says hopelessly adding a fourletter word 
ms ovadiya and her two daughters age 11 and 8 have had no 
place of their own for the last four years they have lived in a 
shed at the tel aviv suburb of petah tikva and once broke into a 
government apartment but were removed by police 
her monthly income totals 600 she works parttime as an 
apprentice at a diamondcutting factory and gets alimony from her 
former husband 
the cheapest onebedroom apartment in tel aviv area costs some 
250 to rent and then come municipal taxes and housing expenses i 
cant afford it she explained 
she has been offered affordable mortgage terms if she moves to a 
remote development town 
i dont want to go there why i have to take children from 
their school and search for work there let the immigrants move to 
development areas she said 
others in the tent say they have nothing against the soviets 
they just want equal rights 
our soul hurts give us a chance pleaded eliahu shukrun a 
spokesman for the tent protest movement that calls itself young 
and homeless 
the protesters speak of families of 10 living in twobedroom 
apartments of married children moving in with their parents and 
grandparents 
shukrun said many young couples cannot afford to rent flats in 
jerusalem where prices have jumped to some 450 a month for a 
twobedroom apartment 
by official estimates about 9000 young israeli couples rent 
apartments in jerusalem and a total of 60000 live in rented homes 
across the country 
the average monthly aftertax income for an israeli family of 
four is 1160 but tent protesters say they can only dream of such 
a salary 
their bitterness is directed at the immigrants 
there will be civil war here not because we have something 
against the immigrants the opposite is true but they push us 
out said shukrun 
he has his own recipe for resolving the housing crisis the 
government should release some lands it owns oblige contractors to 
build public housing quickly and for all creating a stock of 
affordable apartments mortgages for israelis should be enlarged 
and the interest reduced he suggested 
meanwhile their struggle is getting nowhere 
a leftist party contributed a tent and their plight won much 
media attention and sympathy from average israelis who express 
their opinions on radio callin shows and letters to newspapers 
but not a single aprtment owner has offered a flat to rent at a 
reasonable price 
the government also has nothing to offer except plans to set a 
ceiling for housing prices and talk of better mortgage terms for 
israelis 
in the meantime the crisis deepens israel is expected to run 
out of its 20000 vacant rental units in four months and exhaust 
its supply of alternate housing three months later 
the housing ministry seeks 60000 new housing starts this year 
but ground has been broken for only 7000 new units arguments with 
local firms and the construction workers union still block import 
of prefabricated housing 
some protesters like a man who identified himself only as eran 
are pessimistic 
i dont know how long it will last he said so far its 
not that bad here but then winter starts 
</TEXT>
