<DOCNO> AP900623-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
colliding plates of earths crust beneath 
arabia and eurasia unleashed irans catastrophic earthquake the 
same smashup triggered the 1988 seismic disaster in soviet armenia 
the movement of the giant crustal plates squeezes iran from 
both sides like when you want to crack a nut mansour niazi an 
iranian seismologist at lawrence berkeley laboratory said friday 
armenia and iran both are within the alpide seismic belt which 
stretches roughly from greece east to the himalayas 
it is a region in which several plates of earths evermoving 
crust collide in a process once known as continental drift but now 
called plate tectonics 
in the eastern part of this belt the plate beneath india 
smashes northward into the eurasian plate uplifting the himalayas 
in the western end the plate that carries arabia is moving 
northeast about two inches per year as it collides with eurasia 
that collision ultimately caused both the dec 7 1988 armenian 
quake and thursdays quake in northern iran as well as many 
turkish temblors said niazi and bob sharp a us geological 
survey geologist who has worked in both armenia and iran 
niazi said the armenian quake happened near the boundary where 
the arabian and eurasian plates hit each other 
in contrast this weeks iran quake happened near the boundary 
of two smaller microplates that are being squished between the 
larger plates niazi said the smaller plates are located beneath 
the southern caspian sea and the central iranian plateau 
the armenian quake which measured 69 on the richter scale 
killed at least 25000 people the iranian quake with a magnitude 
estimated between 73 and 77 and killed at least 40000 
according to irans mission to the united nations 
many of the worlds most seismically active areas are located 
where a crustal plate beneath an ocean smashes into or slides past 
a plate beneath a continent such as along the west coasts of north 
and south america 
the earthquake belt from greece to the himalayas is the worlds 
most seismically active boundary between colliding continental 
plates niazi said during a telephone interview from berkeley 
a us geological survey list shows that from 1960 to 1989 iran 
was hit by 54 earthquakes that either measured 65 or larger or 
that caused deaths or significant damage 
the northeastsouthwest squeezing of the arabian and eurasian 
plates or the microplates between them created mountains including 
those that stretch from the armenian epicenter in the caucasus 
mountains to irans elburz mountains south of the estimated 
epicenter of thursdays jolt 
sharp speculated the quakes might be linked not only by the 
largescale plate motions but in a manner similar to a crack 
propagating down a grain in a board although the roughly 400 
miles between them suggests otherwise 
preliminary estimates placed the epicenter under the caspian 
sea and sharp speculated the quake might have happened on the 
astara fault niazi said that based on damage reports he believed 
the epicenter was farther south closer to rasht 
the area hit by thursdays disaster has been relatively quiet in 
the past 1000 years with the most recent big quakes in 893 and 
1678 sharp and niazi said that suggests the area was an 
unrecognized seismic gap a locale overdue for a devastating 
quake because they have happened there historically but not 
recently niazi said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

