<TEXT>
here are some facts in the northern spotted 
owl controversy 
northern spotted owl strix occidentalis caurina a reclusive 
brown bird that lives in oldgrowth forests of the pacific 
northwest it can be found from southern british columbia through 
western washington and oregon into northern california as far south 
as san francisco bay 
population estimated at 3000 to 5000 pairs its numbers have 
declined dramatically as twothirds of its habitat has been 
destroyed from years of intense logging 
endangered species act listed as threatened under the act the 
owl will be protected by federal law under the law no one may 
harm or hunt the bird nor destroy its living environment through 
logging or other economic means it prohibits government lumber 
sales that would jeopardize the bird 
economic impact industry estimates claim some options for 
protecting the owl could put as much as 3 million acres of 
oldgrowth forest in washington oregon and northern california off 
limits to logging cost 28000 logging jobs over 10 years and cut 
in half federal timber harvests in the northwest the federal 
government as well as states and local governments in the region 
stand to lose millions of dollars from timber sales 
history environmentalists sought protection for the bird in 
the mid1970s the interior department under the reagan 
administration declined to intervene a 1988 federal court ruling 
directed the department to reopen the case in 1989 the us fish 
and wildlife service proposed protecting the bird under the 
endangered species act a final decision to do so was made friday 
effective july 23 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

