<TEXT>
a chemical cousin of the tranquilizer 
valium and a chinese herbal root long used to induce abortions are 
among dozens of drugs being tested to fight aids researchers 
reported 
doctors described the search for new aids drugs friday at the 
sixth international conference on aids which continues through the 
weekend 
the valium derivative called tibo was found when scientists 
from the institute for medical research in leuven belgium 
screened hundreds of compounds for potential power against aids 
dr rudi pauwels said tibo blocks viral reproduction at levels 
100 times lower than ddc and 3000 times lower than ddi those two 
stillexperimental aids drugs are nearing approval for routine use 
tibo is in early stages of human testing in europe 
the drugs provide hope to infected people who cannot tolerate 
azt the only medicine approved for routine use in people infected 
with hiv the virus that causes aids 
many doctors believe a combination of medicines not just a 
single drug will provide the best chance of keeping healthy the 
estimated 1 million to 15 million americans with hiv 
while doctors and scientists listened to highly technical talks 
inside moscone center demonstrators outside held the latest of 
what have been daily thematic protests 
the focus of fridays action by the aids coalition to unleash 
power or act up was a contention that women children and 
minorities are excluded from research treatment and other services 
women made up most of the more than 200 people at the march and 
diein which resulted in about 140 arrests for blocking an 
intersection 
among the most controversial presentations of the fiveday 
meeting was a report on compound q the chinese herbal medicine 
the treatment is being tested by a community group outside the 
usual control of medical schools and hospitals that ordinarily 
evaluate new medicines 
at this stage we have seen a major and dramatic change in 
what happens to these patients said martin delaney 
delaney is director of san franciscos project inform a group 
that advocates quickly giving people with aids any available 
information about potential medicines 
in its experiment the group has tested compound q on 46 
patients for 116 days before the treatment their helper t cells 
the primary target of the aids virus had been steadily declining 
but after treatment the loss stopped or even reversed itself in 38 
of them 
dr arnold relman editor of the new england journal of 
medicine called delaney irresponsible for releasing his conclusion 
without providing data to back it 
compound q apparently works by stopping infected blood cells 
known as macrophages from manufacturing new copies of the aids 
virus 
another new class of drugs being developed at roche products 
ltd in england takes a different approach dr noel roberts said 
the medicine inhibits the production of viral protease an enzyme 
the virus uses to cut up the proteins that it uses to build new 
copies of itself 
at fridays session researchers also presented data about 
potential aids vaccines 
closest to widespread testing are vaccines that will boost the 
immune system of people who are already infected with the aids 
virus or help prevent infected women from spreading the microbe to 
their children during pregnancy 
further off are vaccines that will keep uninfected people from 
catching the virus 
wayne koff chief of the aids vaccine research branch at the 
national institute of allergy and infectious diseases said the 
most promising human vaccines should be ready for largescale 
testing in two or three years and it will take two or three more 
years to determine their effectiveness 
so were still looking at the midtolate 1990s as a minimal 
time frame for selection of a vaccine for general use koff said 
i think there is reason to be more optimistic now in 1990 
than at any previous international aids conference he said 
some 30 approaches toward the development of vaccines are being 
studied koff said and half a dozen vaccines are being tested or 
are about to be tried in humans 
