thieves can steal a general motors corp car 
faster than the time it takes to watch a camaro commercial say 
police officials in some of the nations largest cities 
police faced with a younger generation of thieves blame gm 
steering columns for making the companys cars the easiest to heist 
thieves are not brain surgeons said michael graziose a new 
york detective it takes someone who dropped out of high school 
30 seconds to steal one of those cars 
los angeles police chief daryl f gates said in a letter to gm 
that children as young as 12 are easily outwitting the present 
security design system of your vehicles 
concerned gm executives summoned police to detroit in april to 
discuss the trend after the meeting the automaker said it would 
include antitheft electronic keys as standard equipment on nearly 
all 1994 cars and alter the muchmaligned steering columns which 
also are used in some chrysler corp models 
the company also plans structural changes in its steering 
columns said robert stempel gms chairmanelect he declined to 
be specific however saying technical details would tip thieves 
off on how to penetrate the new columns 
its not an endall to the theft problem but it helps 
stempel said in a recent interview 
until the changes are in place however gm will produce 
hundreds of thousands of cars police say are exceptionally 
vulnerable to theft 
