<TEXT>
hoverspeed great britain completed a 
recordbreaking sprint across the atlantic saturday lowering the 
best time for a passenger ship by two hours and 48 minutes the 
owners said 
the ship passed the bishop rock light off the isles of scilly at 
14 seconds after 825 am local time or three days seven hours 
and 52 minutes after departing from new york said brian reese a 
spokesman for the hoverspeed project in london 
the record had been held by the ss united states which made 
the crossing in three days 10 hours and 40 minutes in july 1952 
john lloyd captain of the 242foot craft said he expected to 
claim the hales trophy despite controversy over the ships design 
hoverspeed project spokeswoman lynn harvey said the hales trust 
keeper of the trophy had confirmed last year that hoverspeed great 
britain was eligible 
however she said the curators of the mercantile marine museum 
on long island ny where the trophy is kept maintain it was not 
valid because the catamaran will not operate a transatlantic 
service and had no passengers aboard for the record run 
hoverspeed great britain made its crossing with a 10man british 
and australian crew 
the tasmanianbuilt catamaran propelled by diesel engines and 
water jets and capable of 40 knots averaged 366 knots on the 
crossing reese said 
hoverspeed great britain was designed to carry 90 cars and 450 
passengers across the english channel between portstmouth england 
and cherbourg france the first of five of the design it is 
expected to cut the fivehour travel time in half 
hoverspeed is a subsidiary of sea containers ltd 
</TEXT>
