<TEXT>
the government has released the last of 22 
political detainees held without trial for more than three years 
under security measures that date to british colonial rule 
the 22 were arrested in may 1987 for allegedly forming a 
clandestine communist network aimed at overthrowing the 
government and establishing a marxist state 
authorities accused them of infiltrating an opposition party a 
lawyers association the roman catholic church and an amateur 
theatrical company 
the last of the detainees 43yearold vincent cheng was given 
his conditional release from prison tuesday 
but cheng and at least 15 other former detainees are still 
subject to restrictions on their freedom of expression association 
and movement 
cheng and the others were arrested under the internal security 
act which allows for arrest without charge and indefinite 
detention without trial no evidence has to be made public against 
those detained 
british colonial authorities introduced the security act in 1948 
to deal with a communist insurrection in what was then malaya 
singapore was part of the independent malaysian federation until it 
withdrew in 1965 
the internal security act can still be used by authorities in 
malaysia and singapore to detain anyone considered to be a risk to 
national security 
opposition members in the parliaments of both countries say the 
need for such sweeping powers has long passed some contend that 
authorities have used the internal security act to suppress 
legitimate dissent 
deputy prime minister goh chok tong who is scheduled to take 
over from prime minister lee kuan yew in november said i know 
that the isa is a powerful tool and in the wrong hands can do 
harm but i also know that singapore cannot be governed without the 
isa 
human rights groups in britain and the united states have said 
that arrests in recent years under the security act have been 
politically inspired 
the communist insurgency formally ended nov 26 when ceasefire 
agreements among the guerrillas and the malaysian and thai 
governments were signed at hat yai in southern thailand 
at that time singapores home affairs minister shunmugam 
jayakumar told parliament that even with the end of hostilities 
the security act was still needed to deal with other potential 
threats including religious extremism espionage international 
terrorism and subversion 
in kuala lumpur the malaysian capital home affairs minister 
megat junid told parliament on thursday that malaysia still held 86 
people under its internal security act 
malaysian prime minister mahathir mohamad said recently he had 
no plans to abolish the security act because it was very useful in 
a multiracial society 
 
