<TEXT>
japan outinvested the united states in 1989 
for the first time as americans again failed to keep pace their 
major trading partners according to a report on competitiveness 
released saturday 
the report prepared by the council on competitiveness tracks 
us economic performance since 1970 compared with japan west 
germany great britain france canada and italy 
america is looking like an aging athlete still on top but 
trying to ignore all the younger talent that is breaking into the 
lineup said kent hughes president of the council 
in 1989 japan spent 549 billion to modernize and expand its 
industries compared with 513 billion for the united states even 
though the us economy is more than twice the size of japans 
this marks the first time that any country has outinvested 
the united states in plant and equipment in absolute terms since 
world war ii the report said 
in effect hughes said japan is putting twice the tools 
in the hands of the japanese worker 
the groups index being released in advance of the july 911 
economic summit of the group of seven industrial powers in houston 
tracks economic performance in four areas living standards worker 
productivity trade and investment 
on the positive side the united states regained its position as 
the worlds largest exporter supplanting west germany which had 
held the no 1 spot since 1986 
us exports totaled 364 billion compared with 3414 billion 
for west germany and 2739 billion for japan however americans 
are also the worlds biggest importers and the united states ran a 
1086 billion deficit the sixth year in a row the gap topped 100 
billion 
americans continued to enjoy a higher standard of living than 
residents of all of the other countries except germany however 
the other countries are catching up having increased their 
standard of living 50 percent since 1972 compared with a 34 
percent improvement in the united states 
the council founded in 1986 is composed of officials from 
business labor and higher education its goal is to improve the 
ability of american companies to compete in world markets 
 
