<TEXT>
james edward pop pough was known 
as a reliable working man with a sometimesviolent temper but the 
rage that turned him into a mass murderer remains a mystery 
after the shooting spree last monday that killed eight random 
victims and wounded five more investigators were left with one big 
question why 
it is probably a question that no one will be able to 
answer police sgt steve weintraub said friday 
experts say a split with his wife and having his car repossessed 
likely helped spur the shooting spree in an auto finance office 
even though both setbacks occurred months earlier 
pough 42 entered the general motors acceptance corp office 
workers armed with a 30caliber semiautomatic rifle and a 
38caliber pistol and without warning began shooting employees and 
customers alike 
after coldly stalking workers cowering under the desks and 
firing at them pointblank pough put the pistol to his head and 
killed himself 
initially authorities though the auto repossession was the sole 
motive for the attack but then pough was linked to the shootings 
of four people including two who died in his neighborhood the 
weekend before the finance company rampage 
the motive for those shootings is unknown 
what really drives homicidal behavior is rage said helen 
morrison a psychiatrist who heads the evaluation center in 
chicago which studies the psychology of violent behavior 
criminology experts say deep rage coupled with frustration over 
jobs relationships or life in general is a common denominator to 
most mass killing 
jack levin coauthor of mass murder americas growing 
menace said the shootings probably were triggered by the loss of 
his wife and car in the same month january 
his car was repossessed and gmac had sent him a bill for 6394 
but finance company officials said they last had contact with pough 
in march 
levin said the triggering event doesnt have to be 
immediately before the massacre and doesnt even have to be tragic 
from the casual observers point of view 
it may just be the straw that broke the camels back said 
levin a sociology professor at northeastern university in boston 
most of these mass killings look more random than they actually 
are 
he may have been trying to kill gmac as a corporate entity 
levin said or striking out at society at large by launching the 
attack on the office in the citys suburban baymeadows area 
we dont know what sort of crazy maniacal fantasies were 
going through his mind said dr ernest miller a psychiatry 
