<TEXT>
the socialist party of prime minister 
felipe gonzalez won a decisive victory saturday in regional 
elections in his native region of andalusia according to partial 
returns 
the balloting was seen as a test of the socialists strength 
after eight years in power in madrids central government and in 
andalusia 
the socialists have been hit by a 6monthold scandal involving 
the brother of deputy prime minister alfonso guerra under 
investigation for alleged influencepeddling in seville 
with 6515 percent of the vote counted the socialists had 4997 
percent of the ballots cast capturing 61 seats in the 109member 
regional parliament said andalusian regional government minister 
manuel gracia 
if the results hold up it would be a slight improvement on the 
socialists showing in the last regional elections in june 1986 
when they won 465 percent of the vote and 60 seats in the 
andalusian parliament 
however gracia estimated that the voter turnout was only about 
54 percent compared with 70 percent in the 1986 balloting which 
coincided with national elections 
based on the partial returns socialist lawyer and former 
national labor minister manuel chaves 44 was expected to become 
andalusias new prime minister 
the final results were not expected until early sunday gracia 
said the polls opened at 9 am and closed at 8 pm 
gonzalezs party needed at least 55 seats to retain the majority 
it first won in andalusias parliament in 1982 the same year the 
socialists swept into power in the national government in a 
landslide victory 
the main opposition force remained the conservative popular 
party gracia said the partial returns showed the popular party 
winning 2079 percent of the vote for 24 to 26 seats in 1986 the 
party took 234 percent and 28 seats 
the communistled united left coalition had 1293 percent of the 
vote and 11 to 13 seats a loss in support from 1986 when it won 
176 percent and 19 seats 
the biggest gains were registered by the populist regional 
andalusista party which was picking up 1154 percent of the vote 
and was expected to win nine seats gracia said in the last 
election the andalusistas had 62 percent and two seats 
