<DOCNO> AP900623-0143 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
shakespeare fans with ready cash and a taste for 
grandeur will have a chance to buy a piece of history when the 
title of lord of the manor stratforduponavon is auctioned on 
july 19 
the title which dates from the end of the seventh century is 
britains most expensive having been sold two years ago for 
150500 
it will be part of a sale of english literature history books 
and manuscripts at sothebys auction house in london the company 
announced in a sale catalog issued friday sothebys did not say 
who owned the title 
lordships of the manor are the oldest titles in england 
predating the norman conquest of 1066 but their significance is 
largely symbolic today and they carry no rights to land houses or 
a seat in the house of lords 
the owner does not become a lord but can write lord of the 
manor of stratforduponavon after his or her name 
the sunday times said the seller of the title was donald wilson 
a commoner who bought it from lord sackville 
the rapidity with which the title has been put back on the 
market suggests that this quaint industry the selling of 
lordships is becoming a speculators game the newspaper said 
david williamson coeditor of debretts peerage was quoted by 
the sunday times as saying i think it is ridiculous people are 
paying huge prices because they think they can call themselves 
lord but they cant these titles mean nothing 
the sunday times said sales of titles are expected to raise 
nearly 7 million this year double the 1989 figure 
william shakespeare was born in stratforduponavon in 1564 
spent much of his life there and was buried in 1616 in holy trinity 
church 
the manor was the keystone of the english feudal system and the 
lord of the manor was the most important person in village affairs 
traditionally the lord gave his people protection in return for 
services and throughout the middle ages the english nobility 
based its power on the ownership of land through the manor 
the powers of the lord gradually diminished as those of the king 
grew 
the title at stratforduponavon is first mentioned as land 
belonging to ethelard subking of the hwicca tribe who granted it 
to egwin who was third bishop of worcester from 693 to 714 
the title passed to successive bishops of worcester for 
centuries until 1549 when it passed to john dudley earl of 
warwick 
on the death in 1553 of king edward vi dudley tried to put his 
daughterinlaw lady jane grey on the throne but he failed and 
was executed the following year 
the title has also been held by the 3rd duke of dorset a 
british ambassador to the court of versailles remembered for 
taking an english cricket team to france as the 1789 revolution was 
erupting 
another title holder was lionel edward 3rd lord sackville 
uncle of a vita sackvillewest a leading light in the bloomsbury 
literary movement of 1920s london 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

