owners of 16 million chevrolet camaro and 
pontiac firebird cars should check their seat belt release buttons 
for damage that could lead to belt failure the government said 
friday 
general motors corp plans a recall of 1984 to 1990 carmaros and 
firebirds to replace or repair the belts free of charge the 
national highway transportation safety administration said adding 
that damaged belt buckles should be replaced immediately 
the problem is caused when the red plastic pushbutton weakens 
from prolonged exposure to radiation and heat from the sun the 
agency said 
this may cause the safety belt to latch improperly or not at 
all greatly increasing the risk of injury in a crash it said 
nhtsa administrator jerry curry said if a safety belt on one of 
the affected cars does not latch or release properly the car 
should be taken in for repair if there is no damage to any of the 
cars four belts owners can await recall letters from gm he said 
owners of vehicles that dont need immediate attention will be 
sent followup letters by the manufacturer for buckle replacement 
as parts become available nhtsa said 
the problem has been investigated by the government since 
august curry said gm voluntarily is conducting the recall 
