<TEXT>
many people who dont live in medellin 
think it is a city of drugs crime and murder where the people walk 
in fear not so 
drugs are scarcely used in the home of the worlds most powerful 
cocaine cartel as in other colombian cities children respect 
their parents and are reverent to the elderly 
all schools public and private require their students to wear 
clean neatly pressed uniforms and to respect their teachers 
girls under age 15 are chaperroned on dates 
speech is formal and respect is the rule in most personal 
relationships even in the heat of a traffic dispute men call each 
other sir 
graffiti is seldom obscene it is more likely to address labor 
disputes guerrillas or the war on drugs 
people dress neatly many gardeners who are paid less than 50 
a month arrive at work in suits and change in the garage 
medellin is a clean city on the rolling hills of an andean 
valley where men with pushbrooms sweep the streets 
there are spanish churches and colonial houses with redtiled 
roofs modern shopping centers and highrise buildings new 
freeways and old flower stalls 
people are kind they will help a visitor who gets lost answer 
questions about medellin and its customs 
they speak with regret of their citys reputation 
