<TEXT>
japans foremost political gadfly conservative 
lawmaker shintaro ishihara has replied to critics of his 
bestselling tract the japan that can say no 
he has come back with a sequel nonetheless japan can still 
say no 
the no in both is to what he says is american domination 
left over from the 194552 allied occupation of japan after its 
defeat in world war ii 
as the two nations marked the 30th anniversary of their revised 
mutual security treaty saturday ishihara is repeating his calls 
for japan to set out on a new course independent of us influence 
the security treaty should be revised ishihara says he also 
wants the entire constitution revised mainly because it was 
imposed by the americans and also because it was translated into 
ugly japanese 
the japanese have a character flaw of lacking spiritual 
independence because the americans forced us to accept the postwar 
constitution he says 
after the war americans pulled the fangs of ghost japan and 
in their place they gave us a pair of uncomfortable fake teeth 
the japanus defense treaty and the japanese constitution 
ishihara writes its time for japanese to wipe away the postwar 
consciousness that has prevented them from standing up to the 
united states 
ishiharas views are shared by few political commentators but 
his notoriety as a flamboyant politician and commentator have made 
him a popular author 
less than a month after its debut japan can still say no 
has become a bestseller kobunsha the publisher says 350000 
copies have been sold since it was released in may ishiharas 
first no book has sold 11 million copies since january 1989 
bootleg translations of the first book which was coauthored by 
sony corp chairman akio morita raised a considerable stir in 
washington in the book both blamed american management for 
declining us competitiveness 
morita later said he regretted his collaboration with ishihara 
