<DOCNO> AP900623-0172 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission 
suffered another in a series of legal setbacks this past week just 
as officials are trying to push legislation through congress to 
expand the wall street watchdogs authority 
on monday the us supreme court let stand a lower court ruling 
that gave regulatory control of hybrid financial products called 
index participations to the rival commodity futures trading 
commission rather than the sec 
previously in unrelated cases a federal appeals court in new 
york narrowed a rule the sec used to prosecute people for insider 
trading and another court in washington struck down an sec rule 
that sought to protect equal shareholder voting rights 
in mondays decision the high court let stand a ruling by an 
appeals court in chicago that only the cftc has the authority to 
regulate a new form of financial trading called index 
participations or ips 
index participations allow an investor to speculate in the 
fluctuations of a basket of stocks without having to buy the 
underlying stocks 
the chicago appeals court ruled that ips contained elements of 
both a security and a futures contract but under the exclusivity 
clause of the commodity exchange act which created the cftc 
products with even the slightest aspect of a futures contract come 
under cftc jurisdiction 
meanwhile the bush administration is trying to push through 
congress legislation that would give the sec authority over stock 
index futures a futures contract that allows investors to 
speculate in the performance of a large group of stocks like the 
standard amp poors 500 without buying the underlying stock 
the proposal has been introduced in the house as a separate bill 
while supporters in the senate plan to include it as an amendement 
to pending cftc legislation 
despite stiff oppositon by leaders of the senate agriculture 
committee and strong administration lobbying the measure has been 
delayed from going to the floor for a vote as both sides jockey for 
undecided votes 
everyones counting heads the question is whos going to 
force it a vote first said a senate committee staffer who 
spoke on the condition of anonymity 
on friday the senate banking housing and urban affairs 
committee announced it would hold a hearing on the issue july 11 
an ad hoc securities industry group which supports the 
administration proposal says the delay is helping their cause 
i think right now its a tossup a week ago id say we were a 
decided underdog joseph r hardiman president and chief 
executive of the national association of securities dealers said 
thursday 
give us more time and i think well prevail added hardiman 
who is part of the coalition for intermarket coordination 
but will the recent legal setbacks impact the pending 
legislation 
partisans on either side of the issue generally say the impact 
wont be decisive but supports their contention 
i think the court is saying fix the stupid law said 
nicholas a giordano president of the philadelphia stock exchange 
theyre saying we have a crazy quilt of regulation in this 
country and that no sensible person would have done it this way if 
he was starting from scratch 
no other country in the world does it this way so somehow 
weve gotten ourselves into this fix lets correct it and i think 
thats what the court decisions are saying to us and thats what 
were trying to do 
but robert mackay director of the center for study of futures 
and options markets in falls church va said i dont think the 
court said that in the ips case 
rather said mackay the court ruling confirms that the cftc 
was reading the commodity exchange act properly 
mackay a professor of finance at virginia polytechnic 
institute thinks shifting stock index futures control to the more 
restrictive sec is a bad idea 
although he believes the ruling will have little effect on 
congress he said the sec has been overreaching in 
jurisdictional issues and the courts told them that thats the 
message 
but alan bromberg a securities law expert at southern methodist 
university thinks both sides will see whatever they want in the 
decision 
i think its going to be an impetus to the sec group but its 
also going to add ammunition to the cftc supporters its really 
going to be a lobbying fight between the commodity exchanges and 
the securities industry 
in other business and economic news this past week 
philip morris cos agreed to acquire the swiss coffee and 
chocolate giant jacobs suchard ag for 38 billion in a cash deal 
that will create the thirdlargest food company in europe at the 
same time the zurich stock exchange said it was considering 
whether to conduct an insidertrading investigation because details 
of the merger surfaced in the local media while swiss markets were 
still open 
the supreme court ruled that the federal agency which 
guarantees americans pensions the pension benefit guaranty corp 
can force ltv corp to reassume liability for more than 2 billion 
in employee pension plans the company stoped funding three years 
ago the ruling could impede the dallasbased steel and energy 
giants move out of federal bankruptcy proceedings 
the commerce department reported that the us economy grew at 
its second slowest pace in 3 years during the first quarter of 
1990 the gross national product the nations total output of 
goods and services rose at a revised 19 percent annual rate 
during that period the agency said 
